<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-258-816  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 258 816.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  April 24 1989 n535 p57(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fibers change LANscape; FDDI standard paves way for fiber-opticnets. (local-area network, fiber-distributed data interface)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bindra, Ashok.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber-optic local-area network (LAN) revenues will grow at acompound rate of 57.6 percent from $56 million in 1988 to $545million in 1993, with fiber-distributed data interface (FDDI)standard LANs going from zero to $105 million in the same period.andO;The rapid growth in optical LANs is a result of the widerbandwidth, higher speed, immunity to electromagnetic interference,declining costs, and the advent of the FDDI standard.andO;1.6M-bit-sec token-ring optical networks are expected to overtakethe slower Ethernet optical networks in the next five years, withthe latter's market share declining from 70 to 20 percent.andO;Several factors will drive the growth of FDDI LANs: a decline inprice per node from 1988's $25,000 to $1,500 in 1993, FDDI'sdiminishment of multivendor incompatibility problems, improvementof multivendor interoperability, and the advent of FDDI chip sets.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Market AnalysisLocal Area NetworksOptical CommunicationsRevenueOutlookFiber Optics.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   US fiber-optic local-area network revenues. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>